            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1861-10-21T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1861-10-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="158" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d158">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Seward</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Dayton</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 72.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/>
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>,</placeName>
                        <date calendar="gregorian" when="1861-10-21">
                            <hi rend="italic">October</hi> 21, 1861</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your despatch of September 30 (No. 55) has been
                    received. I thank you for your diligence in transmitting the papers concerning
                    our <pb facs="0255" n="255" xml:id="pg_255"/> blockade, which it contains. The
                    blockade is already very effective, quite as much so as any nation ever
                    established. Proceedings are now on foot which will remove the premature
                    objections of the French consul to which you allude.</p>
                <p>I am your obedient servant,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed>
                </closer>
                <postscript>
                    <p>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Wm. L. Dayton</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c.,
                            &amp;c</hi>.</p>
                </postscript>
            </div>
